' plan-59-D Phase 2: a resource that ESCAPES its scope by being returned is
' closed exactly once — by the caller — and zero times by the scope it left.
'
' The assertion is an observable side effect, not an exit code: a leak or a
' premature close is invisible to exit status, which is why §15's guarantee has
' to be checked by watching the handle actually work.
'
' `makeFile` opens a File and returns it. If the callee's scope-exit cleanup
' closed it on the way out, the caller's `fs::writeAll` below would fail on a
' closed handle and the file would read "x" instead of "xy". The file contents
' are therefore the proof: they can only be "xy" if the resource survived the
' return, and the program can only exit 0 if the caller's own scope then closed
' it exactly once.
'
' Two mechanisms keep this correct and they are NOT the same one:
'
'   1. Static deactivation (`deactivate_resource_cleanup`) removes the cleanup at
'      a `RETURN <local>` site, so no close is emitted on the return path at all.
'      This is what already made this shape work before plan-59-D.
'   2. plan-59-D's runtime identity skip compares each cleanup's record pointer
'      against the escaping value and skips close+reclaim on a match. It is the
'      backstop for the cases static deactivation cannot see, and it is inert on
'      every non-escaping path (an error exit stores an error into the pending
'      slot, never a record pointer, so the compare cannot match).
'
' The error path is deliberately still exercised: `writeAll` can fail, and on
' that auto-propagated exit the resource has NOT escaped and must still be
' closed (§15.6). That close is emitted and the identity skip must not suppress
' it.
IMPORT io
IMPORT fs

FUNC makeFile(path AS String) AS RES File
  RES f AS File = fs::openFile(path, "write")
  fs::writeAll(f, "x")
  RETURN f
END FUNC

FUNC main() AS Integer
  LET path AS String = "/tmp/mfb_resource_return_identity_rt.txt"

  RES h AS File = makeFile(path)
  ' Only reachable on a live handle: the callee must not have closed it.
  fs::writeAll(h, "y")
  fs::close(h)

  ' Read it back: "xy" proves both writes landed on the same open handle.
  RES r AS File = fs::openFile(path)
  LET got AS String = fs::readAll(r)
  fs::close(r)
  io::print("contents=" & got)

  ' Repeat the escape many times. A resource closed twice, or never, shows up
  ' here as a failure or as unbounded fd growth rather than as a lucky pass.
  MUT i AS Integer = 0
  WHILE i < 500
    RES t AS File = makeFile(path)
    fs::close(t)
    i = i + 1
  END WHILE
  io::print("escaped=" & toString(i))

  io::print("done")
  RETURN 0
END FUNC
